Prologue
“Please!” Queen Elwin pleaded, “Don’t send her away! She’s just a child!” The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with the royal advisor standing nearby. The queen had given birth to a girl. Just thinking about it, the Ice King couldn’t help but furrow his brow.
The infant looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, and a few strands of blue hair. The Ice King thought that having a daughter would make him look weak. After all, before this, he had only had a son.
“You only have two choices: either kill this child or leave her in the wilderness. Elwin, this is your punishment.” He spat out her name hatefully, as if it were poison. He always did this.
The Frostland Kingdom was not always a kingdom. It once split into two parts, north and south. The north became a non-magical kingdom, while the south was a kingdom full of magical powers. Due to the greed of the north, the two kingdoms fought endlessly until the south proposed a truce.
The Southern kingdom was already in despair, and the royal family was willing to do anything to stop this bloody conflict. They proposed to marry their only princess to the North, making her the Queen of the North and giving birth to a son who would be the future king. Then, the South would merge with the North and establish a unified kingdom. The North accepted the proposal, and Princess Elwin was thus married to Prince Akur.
"Please, my king, for the safety of my child, you can do anything to me—lock me up, exile me, even kill me," implored Queen Elwin, hugging her child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at the queen, his eyes filled with hatred. Perhaps, just perhaps, he might have a little mercy for her. After all, this woman had accompanied him for 22 years, cared for him during his darkest moments, and bore him children.
"Well. The child can live in the palace," said the Ice King, and upon hearing this, the queen breathed a sigh of relief. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisors and Queen Elwin both showed horrified expressions. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. "As you command, my king," she bowed deeply.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to take the queen's daughter to an empty room in Elwin. Once done, he ordered the guards to bring Elwin to the execution ground where all citizens could see.
As the guards escorted her to the execution ground, the citizens saw their only queen—also the kindest queen—about to be executed, and they became very angry. Some cried, some shouted and tried to attack the guards, while others questioned why this was happening; but they all had the same question.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they treating her like this?"
When Elwin approached the wooden stake, the most fearsome person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner of the fire punishment. The former queen Elwin was about to be burned alive. No one should be subjected to the fire punishment, even criminals. In the Frostland, fire punishment was the most cruel penalty.
Alvin was tied to a wooden post, and the king began to recount how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of the Frostlands refused to believe, and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the wooden post, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Carrie, live!" The life of Queen Alvin came to an end.
The hall was deathly silent
In the southern wing of this cold palace, a constant "tapping" sound echoed from the leftmost room. Past servants were always curious about what was inside the room, yet too afraid to get close. The maids moved about the hall, whispering and spreading various rumors. Some believed that the late Ice King's wife, Alvin, was living in this room, waiting to be released.
They were completely wrong. Avery thought as he walked toward the southern wing, the servants walked along the walls, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there are also plenty of rumors about TA, because TA is the only one allowed to enter the room.
He knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you in there?" Avery whispered to this complex door, decorated with snowflakes and crowns, symbols of royalty.
TA didn't know if she would really let him in this time, which was different from before. I still have the bruise from last time. Avery recalled this incident and couldn't help but smile. At that time, Carly threw a book at him, but immediately apologized when she realized who it was.
A soft sound came from the room, as if saying she couldn't go anywhere else but there.
"May I come in?" Avery asked, TA still remembering the consequences of entering without being invited last time.
The room once again echoed with a soft sound. It seemed to say, "Come in." A chill ran through Avery, unsure whether it was from the cold or from that sound. Although he had been there for many years, hearing the sound coming from the room still made Avery feel a bit strange.
"I've come in," Avery said, slowly opening the door. By normal standards, the scene in the room was quite unusual, but that was to be expected. The room was filled with paper. Books were scattered on the floor, the table was broken, and there were many ice sculptures around. There were no windows, and there was almost no light. This room was also colder than other parts of the palace (which explained a lot). The room looked as if it had been hit by a blizzard, everything was in a state of chaos.
The girl in the room was curled up in bed, wrapped in a blanket, reading a notebook. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook are you reading?" Avery asked as he sat by Carly's bed.
